<br>
I see where you are going.  I myself use the words &quot;gay' and fag alot.  Actually, I take it to new levels along the lines of &quot;cumguzzling sewerslut&quot; and other profanities like that.<br>
<br>
Everyday word usage for me comes from the time I spent with my friends, whom all know me and the general intent behind my words.  But there is a time and place for everything.  IE, I dont go into public and start saying fag, gay, and cumguzzling sewerslut.  There is a time and place for everything, and respect for those around you in public and work places is something I can most certainly agree with.<br>
<br>
But on the converse side, I dont know to many homosexual people that actually get offended by such word usage.  In fact, in most cases, they are the most frequent violator of those particular words.  Still not right to use them, just another observation on my part.  After all, the people I hang out with dont get offended by too terribly much in the world outside of religion (pretty much any) or politics.<br>
<br>
Lushe <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uwyndigomoonhowler.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Wyndigo Moonhowler</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Contributing Member</span><br>  Posts: 318<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/3/02 1:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm24.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=21.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: no thats ok</span><hr size=1> I work at a public in the University of California.  I work in a department of about 100 staff and faculty, about 10 of which are (at least, openly) gay.  I've had long conversations with these people and consider them friends.  When people use the word 'fag' and 'gay', it DOES affect them.  They've learned to deal with it, and so they don't blow up at you, but inside, they cringe and hurt everytime they hear it.  It tells them society still hasn't learned to accept and tolerate them.<br>
<br>
2 of these people also happen to be sociologists, and they can confirm that everyday casual language is one of the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> most</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> influential aspects of culture.  The words people use in their everyday lives around their peers gradually shape each other, usually over a long period of time and almost always subconsciously.  <br>
<br>
Think about that. <br>
<br>
I realize it's a hard thing to stop saying.  It took me a year to eliminate any desire to use that word at all.  <br>
<br>
Changing the way you speak isn't going to make this a over-sensitive and boring PC culture, but it's going to tell the world that you care about other people.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ubakxs.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bakxs</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Senior Member</span><br>  Posts: 615<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/3/02 1:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm24.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=21.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Political Correctness</span><hr size=1> Unfortunately (and obviously) I'm a big offender.  <br>
<br>
There was this one time...  I was at work, trying to figure out this problem we were having.  In frustrating, I yelled out--&quot;this is so fuckin' gay!&quot;  Sitting at the desk behind me is one of our store managers, who happens to be homosexual.  The moment I said it, I knew I messed up.  I turned around, appolgized and said, &quot;sorry--that's not what I meant.&quot;<br>
<br>
Like a snowball rollin' down a hill jus' growing bigger, I jus' had to make things worse...<br>
<br>
I said, &quot;No, no... I mean that this project is so damn weak.&quot;<br>
<br>
Which he replied, &quot;So--are you saying that gays are weak?&quot;<br>
<br>
I was dumbfounded...  I jus' appologized once again and went back to figurin' out my GHEY project.  <br>
